# Lessons Learned

Nobody warns you that building your first app feels like death by a thousand cuts. Not because any single thing is hard — it isn't. It's that every step has a small gotcha attached to it. Node isn't installed. The Xcode popup hides behind another window. GitHub stopped accepting passwords years ago and nobody updated the tutorials. Vercel detects the wrong framework. Your .vercel.app URL was already claimed by someone else.

None of it is insurmountable. All of it is annoying. And most people quit somewhere in that gap — not because they couldn't figure it out, but because the accumulated friction made them feel like they weren't cut out for this.

You are cut out for this. The gotchas are just tax you pay once.

## Install your prerequisites before you start building

Node, Git, and a GitHub account. Do it the day before. Don't discover you're missing them when you're in the middle of something. Better yet — install Homebrew first and use it to install everything else. It takes 20 minutes and you only do it once.

| COMMAND  brew install node git gh |
| --- |

## GitHub doesn't accept passwords anymore

Password authentication for Git operations was deprecated in 2021. You need a Personal Access Token or the GitHub CLI. Install the CLI — it's the cleanest solution and the authentication flow takes five minutes.

| COMMAND  brew install gh   then   gh auth login |
| --- |

## Never share a .vercel.app URL publicly

.vercel.app is a shared namespace. Anyone can claim any subdomain. Set up a custom domain on your own domain before you share any link — subdomains are free, take ten minutes to configure, and you own them permanently. The URL governance section of this playbook has the exact steps.

| LESSON LEARNED  tone-fixer.vercel.app was already claimed by someone else before a custom domain was set up. voice-tone-shifter.katehaan.dev is the canonical URL. Don't share .vercel.app links — ever. |
| --- |

## Your .gitignore is a security document

Add it before you add anything else. One accidental commit of google_token.json or a .env file to a public repo means rotating credentials immediately. The templates in the Governance section of this playbook cover the common cases for each repo type. Use them.

| RULE  Create the .gitignore on the first commit. Never the second. |
| --- |

## Cursor + Claude Code beats copying from a chat window

Paste corruption is real. Backticks, smart quotes, and special characters all get mangled when you copy code from a browser into a terminal or editor. When you're building something nontrivial, open Cursor, open the Claude panel, and let it write directly to the file. For simple scripts, use the cp command to copy a downloaded file rather than pasting.

## The design system takes two hours and saves twenty

Don't skip it. Locking in your CSS variables — colors, typography, spacing — before you build a single page means every section you add looks right automatically. The temptation is to get something on screen fast and style it later. Later never comes, and you end up with an inconsistent mess that takes longer to fix than the design system would have taken to set up.

## You will deploy to a 404 at least once

Check your framework preset in Vercel settings. It defaults to Other when it can't detect the project type automatically. Set it to Next.js manually, then redeploy. This costs ten minutes the first time and zero minutes every time after because you'll never forget to check.

## The gap is smaller than it looks

The whole process — from zero to a live, custom-domain app with a design system and a BYOK gate — took one focused session. It wasn't smooth. It also wasn't that hard. The gap between 'I could never build something like that' and 'I just did' is mostly just showing up and not quitting when the third thing in a row doesn't work.

Every person who has a GitHub they're proud of went through the same frustrations. They just kept going.
